<font color="#FF0000">WELCOME BACK JOHN</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 25  6:36:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br><br>
I remember many instances where our returning vets had a hard time finding work. Since coming on line I have met many guys who used their GI benefits to further their educations and now have college degrees.<br><br>
Some, such as myself, never went on to college - however I was and continue to be a skilled, self employed worker. I never was out of work.<br><br>
Perhaps unemployment was the hardest part of the transition for those returning vets..<br><br>
There have been times in the last 3 decades where the unemployment rate has been high. I remember times when there have been massive lay offs which have focused attention on laid off workers (not necessarily vets, though) who lose their self esteem, turn to alcohol, and return home to abuse their families. This is a worst case scenario, but one that I feel is not out of the realm of possibility.<br><br>
Who is to blame for the victimization of the veterans of our generation?<br><br>
The government? There have been broken promises of course, but still many guys did take advantage of those things to which they were entititled.<br><br>
Cook Barela is not entirely &quot;California Dreaming&quot; when he places blame on those who laid a guilt trip on returning vets. The problem I have with his supposition is that I, personally, never looked for validation from those who opposed the war. Rather, I felt that the ones who sent us should have been there to welcome us back.<br><br>
The ultimate irony of being a Vietnam Veteran is the &quot;Welcome Home&quot; we give each other! We were cut loose, but have found each other! I never belonged to many organizations or any fraternities; but none could be as special as being a Vietnam Vet. You guys are stuck with me. &lt;G&gt;<br><br>
I don't want to step on anyones toes right now, but I do want to say this about victimization. It concerns *me* and should not be taken as a slight to those who have been less fortunate in coping.<br><br>
I stopped feeling victimized once I gave up the bitterness and hostility that I harbored for a long time after returning from Vietnam. Once I found it in my heart to forgive those who I was angry with, I found living much easier and satisfying. <br><br>
The way to let go of the resentment and bitterness (which is easily harbored, yes, even nurtured) is to look at the things that we are blessed with. I have so much, I can't help but wonder why I received them.<br><br>
This is driven home especially when I notice people who are less fortunate than I. I opened my eyes long ago, and ultimately have God to thank.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman#greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


